hook.real_world_problem:
You have a product catalog with 100,000 items. A customer scans a barcode (SKU) and you need to find that product instantly. With ArrayList:

```java
List<Product> catalog = new ArrayList<>();  // 100,000 products
// ...
// Find product by SKU:
Product found = null;
for (Product p : catalog) {            // scans ALL 100,000 on average
    if (p.getSku().equals(scannedSku)) {
        found = p;
        break;
    }
}
```

At best, the product is first and you check once. At worst (or average), you check 50,000 items. That's slow. At 10,000 scans per minute in a busy store? Your app lags.

With HashMap:

```java
Map<String, Product> catalog = new HashMap<>();
// Build once:
for (Product p : allProducts) catalog.put(p.getSku(), p);

// Lookup — EVERY TIME:
Product found = catalog.get(scannedSku);  // O(1) — one operation
```

**One operation.** No loop. No matter how big the catalog.

This is what HashMap does: it trades a bit of memory for instant key-based lookup. It's one of the most important data structure decisions you'll make as a developer — and after today, you'll know when and how to use it.

concept_explanation.intro:
A **HashMap** stores **key-value pairs**. Given a key, you retrieve the corresponding value — in O(1) average time.

```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

// Declare
Map<String, Integer> scores = new HashMap<>();

// Put (key, value)
scores.put("Aisha", 95);
scores.put("Raj", 87);
scores.put("Priya", 92);

// Get by key
int aishaScore = scores.get("Aisha");  // 95

// Check key exists
boolean hasRaj = scores.containsKey("Raj");  // true

// Size
int count = scores.size();  // 3

// Update (same key → overwrites)
scores.put("Raj", 89);  // Raj's score is now 89

// Remove
scores.remove("Priya");

// Default if missing
int vikramScore = scores.getOrDefault("Vikram", 0);  // 0 (not in map)
```

Three things to note:
- Declare as `Map<K,V>` (interface), create with `new HashMap<>()`
- Keys are UNIQUE — putting same key twice OVERWRITES the value
- Keys and values are both objects (use Integer not int)

concept_explanation.map_vs_list:
Quick comparison to know when to reach for which:

| Question | Use |
|----------|-----|
| Need elements in ORDER? | `List<T>` |
| Need fast LOOKUP by a key? | `Map<K,V>` |
| Need to COUNT occurrences? | `Map<Item,Integer>` |
| Need to GROUP items? | `Map<Key,List<Item>>` |
| Need fast EXISTENCE CHECK? | `Set<T>` (Topic 6.3) |

**Rule of thumb**: if you find yourself searching a list by ID, name, or any unique attribute — that's HashMap territory.

```java
// ArrayList approach: O(n) search
for (User u : users) {
    if (u.getId() == targetId) return u;
}

// HashMap approach: O(1)
Map<Integer, User> userById = new HashMap<>();
return userById.get(targetId);
```

concept_explanation.iterating_maps:
Three ways to iterate a HashMap:

**1. Keys only**:
```java
for (String key : scores.keySet()) {
    System.out.println(key);
}
```

**2. Values only**:
```java
for (int score : scores.values()) {
    System.out.println(score);
}
```

**3. Key + Value pairs (most common)**:
```java
for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> entry : scores.entrySet()) {
    System.out.println(entry.getKey() + ": " + entry.getValue());
}
```

`entrySet()` gives you a Set of `Map.Entry` objects, each holding a key-value pair. This is the standard way to iterate when you need both.

**⚠️ HashMap order**: HashMap does NOT guarantee any iteration order. If you need sorted output, sort the keys: `new ArrayList<>(scores.keySet())` then `Collections.sort()`. Or use `TreeMap` (which keeps keys sorted) — covered briefly later.

concept_explanation.frequency_counting:
**Pattern 1: Frequency counting** — the most common HashMap use case.

Count occurrences of each item:

```java
String text = "apple banana apple cherry banana apple";
String[] words = text.split(" ");
Map<String, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();

for (String word : words) {
    freq.put(word, freq.getOrDefault(word, 0) + 1);
}

// Results: {apple=3, banana=2, cherry=1}
for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> e : freq.entrySet()) {
    System.out.println(e.getKey() + ": " + e.getValue());
}
```

**`getOrDefault(key, defaultValue)`** is the key to frequency counting:
- If the word is already in the map: get its current count
- If not: use 0 as the default
- Add 1 and put back

One-liner pattern: `freq.put(word, freq.getOrDefault(word, 0) + 1)`

This replaces what would have been a linear scan: for each word, search the list for it, increment if found, add if not. O(n²) → O(n).

concept_explanation.grouping_pattern:
**Pattern 2: Grouping** — collect items into categories.

```java
// Group students by grade
List<Student> students = ...;
Map<String, List<Student>> byGrade = new HashMap<>();

for (Student s : students) {
    String grade = s.getGrade();

    // Get existing list for this grade, or create new one
    if (!byGrade.containsKey(grade)) {
        byGrade.put(grade, new ArrayList<>());
    }
    byGrade.get(grade).add(s);
}

// Shorter with computeIfAbsent (Java 8+):
byGrade.computeIfAbsent(grade, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(s);
```

Result: `{"A": [Aisha, Priya], "B": [Raj, Vikram], "C": [Anita]}`

**`computeIfAbsent(key, mappingFunction)`**: if key isn't in the map, apply the function to create the value and put it. Returns the (existing or new) value. Cleans up the if-containsKey check.

**Real-world applications of grouping**:
- Products by category
- Orders by status (OPEN, PROCESSING, SHIPPED)
- Employees by department
- Sales by month

concept_explanation.lookup_table:
**Pattern 3: Lookup table** — pre-build a map once, query many times.

```java
// Build once (e.g., at startup):
Map<String, Product> productBySku = new HashMap<>();
for (Product p : loadAllProducts()) {
    productBySku.put(p.getSku(), p);
}

// Query many times — O(1) each:
Product p1 = productBySku.get("SKU-001");
Product p2 = productBySku.get("SKU-542");
Product p3 = productBySku.get("SKU-999");
```

This pattern is EVERYWHERE:
- User sessions: `Map<String, Session> sessionById`
- HTTP routing: `Map<String, Handler> routes`
- Database caches: `Map<Integer, User> userCache`
- Config: `Map<String, String> properties`

**Handling missing keys**:
```java
Product p = productBySku.get("INVALID");  // returns null
if (p == null) { throw new NotFoundException(...); }

// Or with getOrDefault:
Product p = productBySku.getOrDefault(sku, DEFAULT_PRODUCT);
```

concept_explanation.common_operations:
Quick reference:

```java
Map<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

// Check if map has no entries
map.isEmpty()                      // true if size == 0

// Check if key exists
map.containsKey("someKey")         // O(1)

// Check if value exists (not recommended — O(n))
map.containsValue(42)              // searches all values

// Merge or update
map.merge("key", 1, Integer::sum); // if key exists, apply sum; else put 1
// Great for frequency counting: merge(word, 1, Integer::sum)

// Put if absent
map.putIfAbsent("key", "value");   // only puts if key doesn't exist

// Remove with value check
map.remove("key", "value");        // only removes if key maps to value

// Clear all
map.clear();

// Get all keys as Set
Set<String> keys = map.keySet();

// Get all values as Collection
Collection<Integer> vals = map.values();

// Iterate entries
for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> e : map.entrySet()) {
    String key = e.getKey();
    Integer val = e.getValue();
    e.setValue(val * 2);  // can modify value via entry!
}
```

