```java
class Product {
    private String sku;
    private String name;
    private String category;
    private double price;
    private int stock;

    public Product(String sku, String name, String category, double price, int stock) {
        this.sku = sku; this.name = name; this.category = category;
        this.price = price; this.stock = stock;
    }

    // getters...
    public String toString() {
        return "[" + sku + "] " + name + " (" + category + ") ₹" + price + " stock=" + stock;
    }
}

class ProductCatalog {
    private Map<String, Product> bySku = new HashMap<>();

    public void add(Product p) {
        bySku.put(p.getSku(), p);
    }

    public Product findBySku(String sku) {
        return bySku.get(sku);  // null if not found
    }

    public boolean hasSku(String sku) {
        return bySku.containsKey(sku);
    }

    public int size() { return bySku.size(); }
}
```

Put once at startup. Query instantly forever.

```java
public Map<String, Integer> totalStockByCategory(ProductCatalog catalog) {
    Map<String, Integer> stockByCategory = new HashMap<>();

    for (Product p : catalog.bySku.values()) {
        stockByCategory.put(
            p.getCategory(),
            stockByCategory.getOrDefault(p.getCategory(), 0) + p.getStock()
        );
    }

    return stockByCategory;
}
```

The classic `getOrDefault(key, 0) + amount` pattern — accumulating totals by group.

```java
public Map<String, List<Product>> groupByCategory(ProductCatalog catalog) {
    Map<String, List<Product>> groups = new HashMap<>();

    for (Product p : catalog.bySku.values()) {
        groups.computeIfAbsent(p.getCategory(), k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(p);
    }

    return groups;
}
```

`computeIfAbsent` creates the list if the category key is new, then adds the product. Clean and idiomatic.

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
